Reasoning

The bug you described (GetLastOnPath using inverted logic and wrong loop bounds) is a traversal mistake: you must walk the trie following the runes of the key from the root, and every time you reach a node that contains commands you update a "last found" variable. If at any point the edge for the next rune doesn't exist you stop and return the last recorded commands (or nil if nothing was found). The common mistakes you mentioned correspond to:

- Using the inverted existence test (treating child exists as failure or child missing as success).
- Using incorrect loop bounds (e.g. iterating beyond length or not iterating at all).
- Updating last when you shouldn't (e.g. before confirming the node exists).

Below is a corrected, minimal and idiomatic implementation of GetLastOnPath and a unit test that demonstrates expected behavior. If you paste this into your repository adapt the field / type names to match your codebase; the algorithm is what matters.

Corrected implementation (replace the method in your trie implementation)

Your trie probably looks like one of these simple variants:

- type Trie struct { children map[rune]*Trie; commands []int }
- or similar names (lowercase receiver names, different command type)

Replace the existing GetLastOnPath with the following (adjust names/types to match your file):

```go
// GetLastOnPath returns the last non-empty commands slice found on the path for key.
// If no node on the path contains commands, it returns nil.
func (t *Trie) GetLastOnPath(key []rune) []int {
    node := t
    var last []int

    // Walk through each rune in key
    for i := 0; i < len(key); i++ {
        if node == nil {
            break
        }
        child, ok := node.children[key[i]]
        if !ok { // if there is no child for this rune, stop traversal
            break
        }
        node = child
        if len(node.commands) > 0 {
            // update the last commands found so far
            last = node.commands
        }
    }

    return last
}
```

Notes:
- Use !ok to detect missing child and stop.
- Update last only after we have navigated to the child node and confirmed it has commands.
- Stop traversal when there is no child for the next rune.

