[USER]
Please solve this issue: Stempel trie GetLastOnPath returns incorrect results

#### Description

The `GetLastOnPath` method in the Polish Stempel analyzer's trie implementation is returning incorrect results. The method appears to be using inverted logic conditions and incorrect loop bounds, causing it to fail to properly traverse the trie and return the expected command sequences.

#### Steps/Code to Reproduce

```go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "github.com/blevesearch/bleve/v2/analysis/lang/pl/stempel"
)

func main() {
    // Create a simple trie with some test data
    trie := stempel.NewTrie()

    // Add some test commands and paths
    key := []rune("test")
    result := trie.GetLastOnPath(key)

    fmt.Printf("Expected: valid command sequence\n")
    fmt.Printf("Got: %v\n", result)

    // The method should return the last valid command found on the path
    // but currently returns unexpected results due to logic errors
}
```

The issue manifests when trying to use the Polish stemmer with certain word patterns where the trie traversal logic fails to correctly identify and return the appropriate stemming commands.

[ASSISTANT]
Reasoning

The bug you described (GetLastOnPath using inverted logic and wrong loop bounds) is a traversal mistake: you must walk the trie following the runes of the key from the root, and every time you reach a node that contains commands you update a "last found" variable. If at any point the edge for the next rune doesn't exist you stop and return the last recorded commands (or nil if nothing was found). The common mistakes you mentioned correspond to:

- Using the inverted existence test (treating child exists as failure or child missing as success).
- Using incorrect loop bounds (e.g. iterating beyond length or not iterating at all).
- Updating last when you shouldn't (e.g. before confirming the node exists).

Below is a corrected, minimal and idiomatic implementation of GetLastOnPath and a unit test that demonstrates expected behavior. If you paste this into your repository adapt the field / type names to match your codebase; the algorithm is what matters.

Corrected implementation (replace the method in your trie implementation)

Your trie probably looks like one of these simple variants:

- type Trie struct { children map[rune]*Trie; commands []int }
- or similar names (lowercase receiver names, different command type)

Replace the existing GetLastOnPath with the following (adjust names/types to match your file):

```go
// GetLastOnPath returns the last non-empty commands slice found on the path for key.
// If no node on the path contains commands, it returns nil.
func (t *Trie) GetLastOnPath(key []rune) []int {
    node := t
    var last []int

    // Walk through each rune in key
    for i := 0; i < len(key); i++ {
        if node == nil {
            break
        }
        child, ok := node.children[key[i]]
        if !ok { // if there is no child for this rune, stop traversal
            break
        }
        node = child
        if len(node.commands) > 0 {
            // update the last commands found so far
            last = node.commands
        }
    }

    return last
}
```

Notes:
- Use !ok to detect missing child and stop.
- Update last only after we have navigated to the child node and confirmed it has commands.
- Stop traversal when there is no child for the next rune.

Unit test demonstrating correct behavior

Add a unit test to confirm behavior with prefixes and full-key commands:

```go
package stempel

import "testing"

func TestGetLastOnPath(t *testing.T) {
    trie := NewTrie() // use your constructor

    // helper to add a command to a path
    // adapt Add or Insert to your actual API; below is a sketch
    trie.Insert([]rune("te"), []int{1})   // command at prefix "te"
    trie.Insert([]rune("tes"), []int{2})  // command at prefix "tes"
    trie.Insert([]rune("test"), []int{3}) // command at full key "test"

    // full key should return the last command on path ("test" -> {3})
    if got := trie.GetLastOnPath([]rune("test")); !equalIntSlices(got, []int{3}) {
        t.Fatalf("expected [3], got %v", got)
    }

    // prefix that stops at "tes" (e.g. key "teste" walks "test" then fails)
    if got := trie.GetLastOnPath([]rune("teste")); !equalIntSlices(got, []int{3}) {
        t.Fatalf("expected [3] for 'teste', got %v", got)
    }

    // key that only matches first prefix "te"
    if got := trie.GetLastOnPath([]rune("team")); !equalIntSlices(got, []int{1}) {
        t.Fatalf("expected [1] for 'team', got %v", got)
    }

    // key with no path should return nil
    if got := trie.GetLastOnPath([]rune("unknown")); got != nil {
        t.Fatalf("expected nil for 'unknown', got %v", got)
    }
}

func equalIntSlices(a, b []int) bool {
    if a == nil && b == nil { return true }
    if (a == nil) != (b == nil) { return false }
    if len(a) != len(b) { return false }
    for i := range a {
        if a[i] != b[i] { return false }
    }
    return true
}
```

